word_summaries_chapter_107:
  107:1:1:"The first word of verse (107:1) is divided into 3 morphological segments. An interrogative <i class=\"ab\">alif</i>, verb and subject pronoun. The prefixed <i class=\"ab\">alif</i> is an interrogative particle used to form a question and is usually translated as \"is\", \"are\", or \"do\". The perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is second person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā hamza yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر أ ي</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">التاء</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  107:1:2:"The second word of verse (107:1) is a masculine singular relative pronoun."
  107:1:3:"The third word of verse (107:1) is a form II imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">kāf dhāl bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ك ذ ب</span>)."
  107:1:4:"The fourth word of verse (107:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and noun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">bi</i> is usually translated as \"with\" or \"by\". The noun is masculine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">dāl yā nūn</i> (<span class=\"at\">د ي ن</span>). Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  107:2:1:"The first word of verse (107:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and demonstrative pronoun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The demonstrative pronoun is masculine singular."
  107:2:2:"The second word of verse (107:2) is a masculine singular relative pronoun."
  107:2:3:"The third word of verse (107:2) is an imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">dāl ʿayn ʿayn</i> (<span class=\"at\">د ع ع</span>)."
  107:2:4:"The fourth word of verse (107:2) is a masculine singular noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">yā tā mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ي ت م</span>)."
  107:3:1:"The first word of verse (107:3) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and negative particle. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\"."
  107:3:2:"The second word of verse (107:3) is an imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ḥā ḍād ḍād</i> (<span class=\"at\">ح ض ض</span>)."
  107:3:3:"The third word of verse (107:3) is a preposition."
  107:3:4:"The fourth word of verse (107:3) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṭā ʿayn mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ط ع م</span>)."
  107:3:5:"The fifth word of verse (107:3) is a masculine singular noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">sīn kāf nūn</i> (<span class=\"at\">س ك ن</span>)."
  107:4:1:"The first word of verse (107:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A resumption particle and noun. The connective particle <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"then\" or \"so\" and is used to indicate a sequence of events. The indefinite noun is masculine and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>)."
  107:4:2:"The second word of verse (107:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and active participle. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"for\". The form II active participle is masculine plural and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṣād lām wāw</i> (<span class=\"at\">ص ل و</span>). Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  107:5:1:"The first word of verse (107:5) is a masculine plural relative pronoun."
  107:5:2:"The second word of verse (107:5) is a third person masculine plural personal pronoun."
  107:5:3:"The third word of verse (107:5) is a preposition."
  107:5:4:"The fourth word of verse (107:5) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A noun and possessive pronoun. The noun is feminine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṣād lām wāw</i> (<span class=\"at\">ص ل و</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is third person masculine plural."
  107:5:5:"The fifth word of verse (107:5) is a masculine plural active participle and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">sīn hā wāw</i> (<span class=\"at\">س ه و</span>)."
  107:6:1:"The first word of verse (107:6) is a masculine plural relative pronoun."
  107:6:2:"The second word of verse (107:6) is a third person masculine plural personal pronoun."
  107:6:3:"The third word of verse (107:6) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and subject pronoun. The form III imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is third person masculine plural and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā hamza yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر أ ي</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">الواو</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  107:7:1:"The first word of verse (107:7) is divided into 3 morphological segments. A conjunction, verb and subject pronoun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is third person masculine plural and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">mīm nūn ʿayn</i> (<span class=\"at\">م ن ع</span>). The suffix (<span class=\"at\">الواو</span>) is an attached subject pronoun."
  107:7:2:"The second word of verse (107:7) is a masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">mīm ʿayn nūn</i> (<span class=\"at\">م ع ن</span>)."